s as consumers and as producers under Spanish rule, the early colonial period witnessed a dramatic upheaval in indigenous women's lives. By analyzing the migration from rural to urban areas, interaction with Spanish as well as African society, and the lives of both plebeians and elites, the author provides a thorough picture of this transformational period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362576140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503625761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503625761/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles